	faithHeading="Faith and the Bible in Ethiopia"
	faithBodyHtml={`<p>Ethiopia is one of the oldest Christian nations on earth. About <strong>67% of Ethiopians are Christian</strong> &mdash; roughly 85 million believers. The <strong>Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church</strong> (around 44% of the country) has kept the faith since the 4th century, with fasting, all-night chant, and Scripture in the ancient Ge&rsquo;ez tongue. A fast-growing Protestant movement &mdash; the <em>P&rsquo;ent&rsquo;ay</em> &mdash; now numbers some 23% more.</p><p>The Bible is woven into Ethiopia&rsquo;s very identity. The Ethiopian Orthodox Church holds a broad canon of 81 books, and Ethiopia appears in the Bible&rsquo;s own pages &mdash; the Ethiopian official of <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read/acts/8" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Acts 8</a> who believed and was baptized.</p><p>And yet, amid centuries of liturgy and reverence, many know God more as a holy mystery to be feared than as a Father to be loved. The need is not a first faith. It is to hear, in the Scripture Ethiopia has guarded for 1,700 years, the Father who calls each child His own.</p>`}
